[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:kubernetes-security-hardening/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
